@Node "Installation" "MagicASL.guide/Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Installation of MagicASL
************************

   The provided Installer script will automatically install MagicASL.

   Installation is quite easy even if you want to do it yourself: just
   - copy `Libs/MagicASL.library' to your `LIBS:' drawer,

   - copy `Libs/MUI/#?.mcc'      to your `MUI:Libs/mui/' drawer,

   - copy `C/PatchAsl'           to your `C:' drawer and

   - run  `C:PatchAsl' in your `Startup-Sequence' like this:

     C:SetPatch QUIET
     Run <>NIL: C:PatchAsl
     ...

   If you want, you can also
   - copy `Locale/Catalogs/#?'         to `LOCALE:Catalogs/' and

   - copy `Help/English/MagicASL.guide' to `HELP:english/'.

   @{b}Please note:@{ub} If you have a previous version of MagicASL installed, be
sure to remove it and restore the original `asl.library' in your `LIBS:'
drawer.


@EndNode

@Node "FileRequester" "MagicASL.guide/FileRequester"
@Toc "Main"

The File Requester
******************

   The file requester features a directory list and a volume list, in a
tribute to the good old `req.library' requester and to MFR.  There is a
balance bar between the two lists that allows you to resize them as you
wish.

   ñ If you enter the name of a non-existent drawer in the `Drawer:' field,
     you will be asked if you want it to be created, but only if the
     requester is in save mode.

   ñ If you enter an incomplete name in the `File:' field, the name will
     be completed when you press <RETURN>.  Press <RETURN> again to accept
     the complete name.

   ñ If the file requester is in multiselect mode, it will feature two
     buttons labeled `All' and `None' beside the `File:' field.  Use them
     to select all or none of the files in the list.

   ñ If the file requester is in save mode, you cannot select a file with a
     double click: you must click on `OK'.

     Note that the background for save mode(1) defaults to the list
     background, so you won't notice any difference in save mode unless
     you configure a different background in the preferences.


Here you can find more informations on some aspects of the file requester:
@{" Menu    " Link "FileReqMenu"}                Some nice functions.
@{" Caveats " Link "FileReqCaveats"}                Beware...

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The original ASL file requester used a black background in save
mode, which looked really ugly.  The idea in itself is nice, but the
original ASL colors are the worst colors one could choose.


@EndNode

@Node "FileReqMenu" "MagicASL.guide/FileReqMenu"
@Toc "FileRequester"

File Requester Menu
===================

   The directory listing in the file requester features two context menus.
The first menu allows you to change the properties of the entry you're on
(the name of the entry will be displayed in the context menu's title):

New drawer...
     Create a new drawer within the current drawer.  You will be asked for
     the drawer name.

Rename...
     Rename the entry.

Delete...
     Delete the entry.  You will be asked for confirmation.

Comment...
     Modify the entry's comment.

Parent...
     Go to the parent directory.  Same as the `Parent' button.

Update...
     Reload the current directory.

     (I know, you want file notification. See @{"Future" Link "Future"}.)

   If you press the right mouse button away from a valid entry (for
example on the list titles), the `Settings' menu appears. The menu is as
follows:

View by £
     The available settings are: Name, Date and Size.

Sort drawers £
     The available settings are: First, Last and Mixed.

Hide icons
     Toggle displaying of icons (i.e. files ending in `.info').


@EndNode

@Node "FileReqCaveats" "MagicASL.guide/FileReqCaveats"
@Toc "FileRequester"

File Requester Caveats
======================

   ñ Using `Sort drawers/Mixed' with `Sort order/Size' will yield strange
     results in the directory ordering: directories don't have a size, so
     they cannot be mixed correctly with files.


@EndNode

@Node "FontRequester" "MagicASL.guide/FontRequester"
@Toc "Main"

The Font Requester
******************

   @{i}This section of the manual will be enhanced in a future release.@{ui}

   The font requester remembers the list of available fonts, so you will
not have to wait for the list being read every time a requester is opened.

   If you need to flush the cached font list from memory, issue the `Avail
FLUSH' command from a shell or use Workbench's `Debug/flushlibs' menu(1).
Of course this works only if the font requester isn't displayed.

   See also @{"Tech notes" Link "Tech notes"}.

The font preview area
=====================

   The area at the bottom of the font requester will show you a preview of
the currently selected font. You can configure the displayed string using
the MUI preferences: look for the FontDisplay configuration page.

   The preview will show designed(2) fonts only, in order to prevent any
delay when you change font(3).  As a side effect, if you select a
non-existent size the preview will show the closest size for that font, or
nothing if that font doesn't have any designed sizes.

   There is a balance bar just above the preview area: it allows you to
resize the preview area at the expense of the font list.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  If you start the Workbench with `LoadWB -DEBUG', a new menu called
`Debug' appears.  The `ROMWack' item starts Amiga's ROM debugger (replaced
by the Simple Amiga Debugging Kernel, known as @{i}SAD@{ui}, in Exec V39).  The
`flushlibs' item does the same as `Avail FLUSH'.  This feature of the
Workbench is not documented on user's manuals.

   (2)  Technically speaking, the `FPF_DESIGNED' flag must be set.

   (3)  When you change font, the font size field stays the same: if the
new font didn't have that particular size ready, the font engine would
calculate it on the fly by rescaling an existing size or, in case of an
outline font, by rendering the given size.  It takes time.


@EndNode

@Node "Tech notes" "MagicASL.guide/Tech notes"
@Toc "FontRequester"

Tech notes
==========

   @{i}This section is intended mainly for developers.@{ui}

MaxFrontPen and MaxBackPen
--------------------------

   During the development of MagicASL I discovered a small debatable point
in the ASL documentation, related to the interpretation of font requester's
MaxFrontPen and MaxBackPen attributes. In the ASL autodoc they are
explained as "the maximum number of pens that are offered to the user";
indeed, the font requester palette gadgets do have `maxpen' buttons.

   According to my logic, though, "max pen" should mean "the maximum pen to
let the user choose", i.e. the palette gadgets should have `maxpen+1'
buttons. This is even more logic if you consider that the default maximum
value is 255: the definition in the ASL autodoc implies that by default you
can't choose the 256th color of a 256-color screen, and in fact you can't
specify 256 pens at all, because these attributes are stored as UBYTEs, so
they can range from 0 to 255 only.

   MagicASL behaves like ASL, but only after I saw that my logic was wrong.


@EndNode

@Node "ScreenModeRequester" "MagicASL.guide/ScreenModeRequester"
@Toc "Main"

The Screen Mode Requester
*************************

   @{i}This section of the manual will be enhanced in a future release.@{ui}

   There is not much to say about the screen mode requester that you don't
know already. You get a list of available display modes and, if the
requesting program asked for them, fields for setting overscan, width,
height, depth and autoscroll mode.

   The author can't yet test the requester on graphic cards or RTG systems
such as CyberGraphX(1).  If you have such a system, please report any
problems.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  The first beta release had problems with CyberGraphX. See @{"History" Link "History"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Preferences" "MagicASL.guide/Preferences"
@Toc "Main"

The Preferences
***************

   The MagicASL preferences allow you to configure the appearance of the
requesters.

   @{i}Note: The preferences are currently in beta stage.  Anything is subject
to change according to users' feedback.@{ui}

   In the following sections you will find more informations on the
configurable items.

   @{i}Note: The font and screen mode requesters are not configurable yet.@{ui}

The Files' Color
================

   You can choose if drawers and files are to be displayed in normal or
@{i}highlighted@{ui} color. By default, drawers are highlighted.

The Files' Font
===============

   The file requester lists (drawers/files and volumes) use the fixed-width
font by default. You can choose among four fonts:

Normal
     normal MUI font (usually the screen font).

List
     list font (often the screen font again).

Tiny
     tiny font.  Select this font if you want to display as much
     information as possible in the requester.

     If you can't decide between tiny and fixed font, I suggest to map the
     tiny font to a small fixed-width font: there isn't much difference
     between fixed-width or proportional for small fonts.

Fixed
     fixed-width font.  I prefer this font for the display of file names.

Displayed Fields
================

   You can choose what information the file requester should display.
Apart from file name and size, which are always displayed, you can choose
to see the file date, time, flags and/or comment.  By default, the
requester will display date, time and comment.

   @{i}Note: It would be easy to display extended file flags as used by `muFS'
and Envoy but, in spite of the notes in this manual, I received no more
than a couple of requests to do so.@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "Compatibility" "MagicASL.guide/Compatibility"
@Toc "Main"

Compatibility with the Real ASL
*******************************

   This chapter lists some ASL features that MagicASL does not currently
have, with a short explanation; most of these misfeatures are a
consequence of MUI, and implementing them is either impossible or against
MUI philosophy.

   Anyway, if you have a program that needs one of these features, let me
know. Philosophy is useless if things don't work.

   See also @{"Known bugs" Link "Known bugs"}.

   ñ All requesters ignore PrivateIDCMP because MUI transcends IDCMP
     messages completely. Basically, MagicASL always behaves as if you
     asked for a private IDCMP port; however, it will call IntuiMsgFunc on
     the reference window.

     The IntuiMsgFunc is most useful for refreshing simple-refresh
     application windows when the user waves requesters over them; MUI
     applications, in particular, should have a minimal IntuiMsgFunc(1)
     just for this purpose.

   ñ All requesters ignore ASLxx_LeftEdge/TopEdge/Width/Height and TextAttr
     because tampering with an application's appearance at this level is
     against MUI philosophy.

     However, when the requester is closed the values of LeftEdge, TopEdge,
     Width and Height will be set correctly, in case someone is using them.

   ñ All requesters ignore `ASLxx_Locale'; MagicASL always uses the current
     locale. This may change in a future release.

   ñ The file and font requesters ignore `ASLxx_HookFunc'. The difficulties
     mentioned in previous releases of this documentation have been sorted
     out; however, I did implement the `ASLxx_FilterFunc' tags only.  In
     fact I'm considering to forget about HookFunc, because I think it
     should be declared obsolete. I'm willing to hear your opinion on this
     subject.

   ñ Reserved fields in the requester structures are used for my very own
     purposes, so evilish programs that peek them will most probably crash.
     Well, that's @{i}their@{ui} problem.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Have a look at the autodoc for `MUIM_Application_CheckRefresh'.


@EndNode

@Node "Known bugs" "MagicASL.guide/Known bugs"
@Toc "Main"

Known bugs
**********

     "Bugs? What bugs? My code doesn't have bugs!"

   Alas, no software I know of is free of bugs.  However, it is better to
know where bugs are, so here it is:

   ñ If you open two requesters at once, then the second requester will
     not show up where you snapshot it. That's because different
     requesters are different instances of the MagicASL application (i.e.
     `MagicASL.1', `MagicASL.2', etc.), so MUI saves different settings
     for each one of them.  This is not really a bug, it's just that MUI
     doesn't allow me to do things in a different way.

   ñ There are also some unimplemented features which shouldn't affect end
     user functionality. See @{"Compatibility" Link "Compatibility"}.

   @{b}Please note:@{ub} There is no doubt that some programs will behave badly
when confronted with MagicASL. Nobody's perfect, or at least not me, so
there will be problems somewhere; but then consider that first of all I
wrote MagicASL for myself, and I started using it well before it was
complete, so I had chances to eradicate any problems I encountered with
the programs I use daily.

   So, if something doesn't work, don't say "MagicASL sucks": tell me which
program behaves badly and wait for me to check it out and see who is wrong.
If the problem is in my code, be sure that I will fix it yesterday.


@EndNode

@Node "Bug reports" "MagicASL.guide/Bug reports"
@Toc "Main"

Bug reports
***********

   If you discover a problem in MagicASL, first make sure that I didn't
know already: read this manual carefully.  Then, please write to the
author (see @{"The Author" Link "The Author"}) and provide the following information:

   ñ The version of MagicASL which shows the problem.

   ñ The exact version of the operating system (see Workbench's `About'
     requester), MUI and any other relevant software.  @{b}This is essential.@{ub}

   ñ Your full Amiga configuration (model, CPU, peripherals, etc.).

   ñ A detailed explanation on how to reproduce the problem.  If I can't
     reproduce the problem, I'll have lots of troubles locating it, and I
     will probably end up thinking it is your fault. Bug reports like "it
     doesn't work sometimes" are definitely not what I need.

   ñ If MagicASL irritates tools like The Enforcer or MungWall, please
     include their output in your bug report.

   If you are missing something in MagicASL, please write to the author
too.


@EndNode

@Node "Future" "MagicASL.guide/Future"
@Toc "Main"

Planned enhancements for the future
***********************************

   ñ There are some more things you could be allowed to configure in the
     preferences:

        - disable vertical bars in the lists;

        - enable displaying of extended file attributes (`muFS', Envoy);

        - percentage width and height of the requester windows.

   ñ Buffering for the file requester. ReqTools has it.

   ñ Directory notification.  You don't want to press `Update' when the
     directory is changing, do you?

   ñ How about a color requester? ReqTools has it, too.  However, standard
     ASL doesn't, so it could cause compatibility problems with future ASL
     releases - unless Amiga Technologies (or whoever will develop AmigaOS
     in the future) adopts MagicASL. (hint, hint)

   ñ I would like to write `muFS'(1) support. Need it? Ask for it!

   ñ The compatibility issues listed before (see @{"Compatibility" Link "Compatibility"}) are of
     course good candidates for future development; tell me if you need
     one.

   ñ I would like to link MagicASL windows in the calling MUI application
     by patching into `MUI_AllocAslRequest()' and `MUI_AslRequest()'.
     This would give every application its own positioned requesters and
     would overcome any refreshing problems.  However, this is a Bad Thing
     since there is no documented way to do so.

   Oh, and a little note... Don't ask for the balance bar positions to be
saved - it's not possible with the current release of MUI.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Short for MultiUser File System, a Unix-like file system for the
Amiga.


@EndNode

@Node "History" "MagicASL.guide/History"
@Toc "Main"

History
*******

V42.1 (31.08.96) - first beta release
=====================================

   This release had severe problems with CyberGraphX and any other program
that might open `asl.library' early in the startup-sequence, when the MUI
assignments usually have not been set up yet.

   Otherwise, it was just a beta: most things worked, most other were
simply missing.

V42.2 (12.09.96) - second beta release
======================================

   - You can select all or none of the files in the file requester via two
     menu items (applicable only when the file requester is in multiselect
     mode).

   - MUI-ASL opens MUI libraries only when needed (i.e. when `AslRequest()'
     is called). This should solve problems with CyberGraphX and other
     programs.

     (reported by lots of people)

   - Enhanced the layout algorythm of the font requester's palette gadgets.
     Previously the layout was a long row of color boxes, which was too
     big to be displayed on deep screens.

     Note that there still could be problems on small screens with many
     colors.

     (reported by <helix2\@ios.com>)

   - MUI-ASL did not check if the requester window did open, so it could
     enter the input loop without a window!  This often happened as a
     consequence of the aforementioned layout problem.  Now an alert is
     shown and the requester is aborted.

   - Corrected an annoying bug: the requester structures were filled with
     current values even when the user hit `Cancel'.

   - Implemented the `New drawer...' function in the file requester.  In
     fact it was there in the previous release too, but I forgot to enable
     the menu item after correcting a nasty bug.

     (requested by Robert Kauffman)

   - Fixed Enforcer hits when MonitorSpec not available for a display mode.

     (reported by Stefan Becker)

   - The `Pattern:' gadget is now above `Drawer:' and `File:' as in the
     real ASL and ReqTools. Previously the `Pattern:' gadget was below
     them.

     (requested by Marcin OrŸowski)

   - The file requester window allows drag'n'drop of icons on it.

     (requested by several people)

   - The file/font requesters correctly highlight the initial file/font.
     However, they don't jump to it. I'm working on this.

     (reported by several people)

V42.3 (03.11.96) - third beta release
=====================================

   - The file requester's context menu has been greatly enhanced.

     (suggested by Christer Bjarnemo)

   - Finally implemented filtering functions.  However, see
     @{"Compatibility" Link "Compatibility"}, for some notes on this subject.

   - Deeply revisited internal notifications. No changes for users.

   - Just discovered that the real ASL doesn't copy the strings for title,
     positive and negative texts, so I don't either.  Those strings @{b}must@{ub}
     be valid throughout the requester's life.

   - Finally implemented IntuiMsgFunc.

   - Now you can type a path (full or relative) in the `File:' field.  The
     path part will be thrown in the `Drawer:' field.

     (requested by Ralph Torchia, Marcin OrŸowski and others)

   - Shuffled some buttons around: changed `All' and `None' functions from
     menu items to buttons; `Parent' is between `OK' and `Cancel';
     `Update' is beside `Drawer:'.

     (requested by Paul Hickman)

   - The buttons in the file requester are not in the cycle chain any more
     (except for `OK' and `Cancel') because you can reach them with
     shortcuts.

     (suggested by Paul Hickman)

   - The screen mode requester doesn't show a display mode at all when its
     MonitorSpec is not available.

     (suggested by Stefan Becker)

   - The string for the font preview area (which is a FontDisplay object)
     is now configurable using the MUI preferences.

   - The depth slider in the screen mode requester now displays the number
     of colors instead of the screen depth. Easier to understand, isn't it?

   - Implemented property information window for the screen mode requester.
     Still very incomplete: lots of numbers but missing actual properties.

   - Localization is here. Some translations are included, although
     incomplete.  Now it's up to you: translate the catalog into your
     preferred language!

   - The file requester can create a non-existing directory for you.

   - Greatly improved behaviour of the file requester when you enter
     non-existent file/directory names or the name of a directory in the
     `File:' field. Too long to explain, try it out yourself.

     (requested by many people)

   - Also added kind of name completion for the `File:' field. Try typing
     the first characters of a drawer/file name, then press <RETURN> and
     enjoy.

     (suggested by Stefan Becker, Rune Jacobsen and others)

V42.4 (11.11.96)
================

   - I somehow copied the BackMan (a backup utility I wrote) install icon
     over the MUI-ASL install icon. Since the MUI-ASL installation script
     was a shell script, clicking on it wouldn't work.

     I wonder for how long this has been wrong - I don't remember messing
     with the icon after the first release.

   - Now this is a rather big mistake: MUI-ASL wouldn't work on Release 3.0
     because I incorrectly assumed that the `locale.library' file of
     Release 3.0 was version 39, when it really was version 38.  My
     apologies to 3.0 users; however, upgrade.

     (confirmed by Kai Nikulainen, reported by many people)

   - Swedish (svenska) translation from Mats Nyman.

   - The string requester was missing a window ID, i.e. its position
     didn't get saved.

     (reported by J—rg M■ller)

   - The file requester's context menu has been split in half. Try it out.

   - The middle mouse button (if you have one) acts as a `Parent' button.

     (suggested by Stefan Becker)

   - Directories are white now.

     (requested by many people)

   - The `OK' button didn't work correctly in the file and font requesters.
     Too bad I didn't notice it yet...

     (reported by Peter Denomy)

V42.5 (internal version, not released)
======================================

   - Open `locale.library' when I really need it, not during library open.

   - The `DispModeInfo' and `DispModeList' classes are no longer public.

   - Recompiled with SAS/C 6.57.

   - Turned off volume list titles.  They are part of MUI's `Volumelist'
     class, so I don't have any control on their appearance; since I can't
     even localize them, it's probably better not to see them at all.

     You will probably figure out what each column means anyway. ;-)

   - MUI 3.7 fixed the Enforcer hit in the `Volumelist' class.

   - Removed the useless titles from context menus.

   - The alternate window size is wider (how much wider depends on which
     requester) and almost as high as the screen.

     (suggested by Paul Hickman)

   - Dutch (nederlands) translation from Rembrandt de Witt.

   - Fixed an old bug in the file requester: if you selected a directory
     using cursor keys while the `File:' field was active and pressed
     <RETURN>, the requester would close instead of entering that
     directory.

   - If the requester is canceled, `IoErr()' now returns 0.  The return
     code was random, causing spurious error message with Visage.

     (reported by Kai Nikulainen)

V40.6 (02.10.97)
================

   - Recompiled with SAS/C 6.58.

   - The library no longer replaces `asl.library'; it is now glued into the
     system by means of a small patch program. See @{"Installation" Link "Installation"}.

   - Changed version number to match Workbench 3.1's `asl.library', which
     is the version I did all my testing with. This will ensure that
     programs looking for a specific release will work correctly, and it
     will also avoid compatibility problems the day a new, official
     `asl.library' appears.

   - Using `MUIM_HandleEvent' in place of `MUIM_HandleInput'.

   - The font requester accepts and displays font names without the
     `.font' suffix.

V40.6b (internal version, not released)
=======================================

   This update corrects several bugs in release 40.6:

   - the install script was missing a parenthesis;

   - `ASLFR_FilterFunc' didn't work;

   - the requester titles were wrong sometimes;

   - finally, I think I have found the bug that caused the screen mode
     requester to crash sometimes.

   Let me tell you a story.  Some time ago I wasted hours trying to make
`ASLFR_FilterFunc' work and I eventually discovered that I wasn't updating
the drawer string in the file requester structure.I corrected the problem
and forgot about it.  In fact I forgot about it so much that one day I
reverted to the non-working code. I didn't realize how big a mistake it
was until some people complained that 40.6 (which was supposed to fix all
known bugs) was broken. @{i}Grrr!@{ui}

   Regarding the install script... Well, you should really test any kind
of script or program again after you change it, shouldn't you?  The script
was working at last, so I split in two that help message I just added (it
was well over one line long), packed things up and uploaded the archive.
Unfortunately `(cat)' wanted one more parenthesis...

V40.6c (internal version, not released)
=======================================

   - Uses `Lamp.mcc' to display an activity LED. See @{"Requirements" Link "Requirements"}.

   - Added some validation to the directory name. You won't be asked if
     you want to create directory `Foo:' when you type the wrong volume
     name.

   - The color buttons in the font requester follow the mouse, as good old
     GadTools gadgets did.

V40.7 (5.12.98)
===============

   - Big change: the official name of this project is now `MagicASL'.

   - At long last, I put together some preferences.  Look for a "MagicASL"
     item in the MUI preferences.

   - `PatchAsl' will not start if it can't find `MagicASL.library'.

   - Russian translation from Oleg Sergeev (translation done by Serge
     Veselov).

     (I received another translation from Oleg some time ago, but I didn't
     include it in previous versions. My apologies.)

   - You can now enter an empty pattern in the file requester, which means
     "show me everything".

   - The font requester's display shows text with the correct pens if the
     `FrontPens' and/or `BackPens' tags are used.

     (reported by Christopher Kossa)

   - Revised shortcuts for all the languages I could test (there were some
     conflicts).

   - If the directory you enter in the `Drawer:' field does not exist, the
     file requester asks if it should create it only if it is in save
     mode. Also, it will not ask you to create a device.

     (reported by Volker RemuÔ)

   - The file requester didn't work on directories with wildcard characters
     (such as `#', `*', `[]', etc.) in their names.  This is a problem in
     `MatchFirst()'/`MatchNext()'.

     (reported by Vidar Andersen)


@EndNode

